<p>Once, one of his playwrights, Zayd (who would later become my husband), wrote a play in which two human beings wake up together only to discover that they are in a cage, a zoo of sorts. Derek, who believed and taught us to believe that plays are, by their nature, lyricalâ€”poetry unfolding on the stageâ€”complimented Zayd on his dialogue but said that the whole play would have to be scrapped unless â€œthe questionâ€ was answered. â€œWhat question?â€ we asked, and he stood up: â€œWhere is the toilet? You think you can have two people in a cage overnight and not tell us where they use the toilet? You cannot.â€</p>

<p>Derek was correct, of course: if the logistics of a narrative are flimsy or absent, then it hardly matters how lyrical its lines are. I have called upon this and additional bits of Walcottâ€™s wisdom countless times in my own writing and teaching. He once said, of another studentâ€™s play, â€œIf a characterâ€™s problem can be fixed with medication, then itâ€™s a story of chemistry, not of tragedy.â€</p>

