<p>Why Iâ€™m Against Redundancy In Stories</p>

<p>https://www.quora.com/profile/Marcus-Geduld
Marcus Geduld,Â Shakespearean director, computer programmer, teacher, writer, likes dinosaurs.
To start with, I will define a â€œstoryâ€ as a linear narrative: a tale of â€œone damn thing after another.â€ There are, of course, stories that arenâ€™t structured that way. I am not going to consider them here, because, in most cases, Iâ€™m donâ€™t find them pleasing. (I have some theories that elevate linear narratives above other narrative structures, by which I mean that the linear form will most please most readers, probably because readers experience life as â€œone damn thing after another,â€ but I wonâ€™t push those theories here. Here, letâ€™s just say that I happen to prefer linear narratives, so Iâ€™m going to discuss storytelling within the framework of that aesthetic.)Â  Because I hate the clunky phrase â€œlinear narrative,â€ from here on, Iâ€™m going to replace it with the word â€œstory.â€ Please indulge me! I know there are other kinds of stories. But for the duration of this essay, I am using â€œstoryâ€ to label just one type of story. In their purest form, stories move FORWARD CAUSALLY. Event one (at the earliest time in the story) causes event two (at a later time), which causes event three (at a still later time) and so on. Readers have this basic template in their heads. Itâ€™s a pleasing template, and they notice when a story veers from it, which isnâ€™t to say that all veers are bad veers. Readers donâ€™t mind veers â€“ in fact they sometimes enjoy them â€“ when they understand the purpose of the veering. For instance if, in a story, Fred goes to a cafe, meets Alice, and then leaves to go to work while Alice remains, the reader will understand (if itâ€™s clear Alice is an important character) why the story stays with her and then, later, travels back in time to catch up with what Fred saw on the way to his office. Such a story breaks from simple linearity, but for a clear reason: it canâ€™t follow Fred and Alice at the same time, because they are in different locations. When a writer handles this badly â€“ say if he makes the Alice subplot bori