I sympathize with your pain, but this attitude is a problem:</p>

<p>â€œPart of me feels that if a story is good enough, then it should not matter if it is plausible.â€</p>

<p>You have put â€œgood enoughâ€ in one category and â€œplausibleâ€ in another, whereas for many readers a story canâ€™t be â€œgood enoughâ€ if itâ€™s implausible. This isnâ€™t the case for all readers, but what I most want from fiction is to forget itâ€™s fiction. If a Tolkien or a Stephen King can get me to really believe, at least for a short time, in Elves or ESP, theyâ€™ve given me a tremendous gift.</p>

<p>Thereâ€™s no shortcut. You simply have to do it. (Or donâ€™t do it and accept the fact that people like me wonâ€™t enjoy your story.) You need to root out the implausibilities and alter them or justify them, making them plausible. And if you canâ€™t immediately figure out how to do that, join the club. Itâ€™s a puzzle, and youâ€™ll have to work at it. Hint: study other peopleâ€™s solutions. Iâ€™ve mentioned some specific ones, below.</p>

<p>I almost didnâ€™t write â€œjustify,â€ because it tends to lead many writers astray. Make sure that your justifications are both intellectually and emotionally satisfying. In other words, if you claim, in chapter six, that faster-than-light travel exists, you canâ€™t justify it by, in chapter nine, quickly explaining that your story takes place in a parallel universe with different physical laws.</p>

<p>Why make me live with disbelief for three chapters? And if youâ€™re going to make up such a radical piece of story logic, it should be affecting your entire world. I canâ€™t buy a Universe thatâ€™s exactly like ours except for faster-than-light travel. Surely theyâ€™d be many ramifications. Think them through. If you do, you can lace them throughout your story, making the FTL revelation plausible when it occurs.</p>

<p>Does that mean no space opera can possibly work? No. Thereâ€™s a good way to work implausibilities into your story: state them up front. â€œStar Trekâ€ and â€œStar Warsâ€ work because FTL travel exists from the get-go, before the reader (or viewer) even has time to fall into a state of belief.</p>

<p>â€œOnce upon a time there was king who could turn invisibleâ€¦â€ works, because weâ€™re trained from childhood to shoot off from a hypothetical premise. In such stories, you neednâ€™t explain where the kingâ€™s abilities come from. â€œTheyâ€™re just magicâ€ works for most readers, but only if magic is part of the world from page one.</p>

<p>â€œOnce upon a time, the King of England ordered his troops â€¦ blab blah blah â€¦ â€œ then, four chapters later, â€œâ€¦ and so he turned invisible â€¦â€ doesnâ€™t work, because you gave the reader three chapters to assume a non-magical framework.</p>

<p>Rule: nothing in fiction should contradict the readerâ€™s mental framework. Whenever something does, the reader will get distanced. And he always has a framework, even while reading the first sentence of the story. If not told otherwise, heâ€™ll assume the story world is the same as the real world. Thatâ€™s the default framework.</p>

<p>â€œToy Storyâ€ immediately establishes an alternative framework. From its opening shots, we learn that in its world, familiar toys are conscious and can move about on their own. But we assume that, aside from this, the filmâ€™s world is pretty much like ours. If, an hour into the movie, Mr. Potato Head started breathing fire, weâ€™d be confused and distanced. Why? Because that would contradict our framework.</p>

<p>Moral: front-load your implausibilities! That can be via extremely straight-forward exposition, such as the text crawl at the beginning of â€œStar Wars,â€ the narration at the beginning of â€œStar Trek,â€ or the opening of â€œThe Hobbitâ€: â€œIn a hole in the ground, there lived a hobbitâ€¦â€</p>

<p>Hereâ€™s how Susana Clarkeâ€™s Dickensian fantasy novel, â€œJonathan Strange and Mr. Norrell,â€ starts:</p>

<p>Some years ago there was in the city of York a society of magicians. They met upon the third Wednesday of every month and read each other long, dull papers upon the history of English magic.</p>

<p>Or you can front-load more stealthily, via dialog and description. Just make sure itâ€™s early dialog or description. Hereâ€™s the opening of â€œGame of Thronesâ€:</p>

<p>â€œWe should start back,â€ Gared urged as the woods began to grow dark around them. â€œThe wildlings are dead.â€</p>

<p>â€œDo the dead frighten you?â€ Ser Waymar Royce asked, with just the hint of a smile.</p>

<p>Gared did not rise to the bait. He was an old man, past fifty, and he had seen the lordlings come and go. â€œDead is dead,â€ he said. â€œWe have no business with the dead.â€</p>

<p>â€œAre they dead?â€ Royce asked softly. â€œWhat proof have we?â€</p>

<p>â€œWill saw them,â€ Gared said. â€œIf he says they are dead, thatâ€™s proof enough for me.â€</p>

<p>[Spoilers:] And just a few pages later, these characters are attacked by what are clearly supernatural creatures. After that, nothing magical or supernatural happens for many chapters, but the mental groundwork has been laid.</p>

<p>Does this mean that if youâ€™ve created a complex sci-fi or fantasy world, with all sorts of differences between it and the real world, you have to front-load all those differences. No. What you have to do is intellectually and (more important) emotionally prepare the reader for them.</p>

<p>Having established that magicians exist, Susana Clarke doesnâ€™t need to immediately tell me that they cause cause objects to levitate. Does she need to tell me theyâ€™re immortal (which is not the case in her novel, but for the sake of argument, letâ€™s say itâ€™s true)?</p>

<p>Thatâ€™s an interesting question. You have to use your judgement. If I know magicians exist in the world, I can probably wait until chapter four and only then find out they can levitate small objects, but if you suddenly tell me (after 100 pages) theyâ€™re immortal and use that as a major plot device, Iâ€™ll be distanced.</p>

<p>Thereâ€™s another hint for you, and itâ€™s a major one: if an implausibility is the solution in the plot, make sure the reader knows about it (or can deduce it) earlier. In other words, if you tell me a character is a wizard, you donâ€™t have to front-load â€œpower of invisibility,â€ but you do have to tell me he can turn invisible before he uses that power to get out a fix. Otherwise, Iâ€™ll smell deus ex machina, which means Iâ€™ll become aware of an authorial hand. Which means Iâ€™ll fall out of a state of belief.</p>

<p>And make sure you donâ€™t tell me about invisibility right before it becomes a solution. I see this screw up constantly on TV. We learn about some new magic ability for the first time at the start of an episode and then it becomes a big solution at the end. (After which, itâ€™s usually forgotten in subsequent episodes.) Thatâ€™s bubble-bursting. It would have worked better if the ability had been brought up one or two episodes earlier, giving me time to shrug and forget about it. The seed would have been planted in my mind, which would have made the solution feel inevitable and grounded in the rules of the world when it happened, later.</p>

<p>So, summing up:</p>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p>Front-load major, categorical differences between the story world and the real world, such as faster-than-light travel or the existence of magic.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Hint at differences which will become major plot points long before they become important, so that they seem like casual facts about the world.</p>
  </li>
</ol>

<p>Iâ€™m not a â€œStar Warsâ€ fan, but itâ€™s interesting to study the film from this perspective, because Lucas had to make his audiences accept both sci-fi (e.g. FTL) and fantasy (e.g. The Force) elements. Notice that he front-loaded the former (via the text-crawl and the opening shot of the space cruiser) and hinted at the latter.</p>

<p>The Force is especially interesting in this regard. [Spoilers:] Lucas understood (consciously or not) that heâ€™d paved the way for a sci-fi world, not a fantasy world, and that if heâ€™d just suddenly plopped magic on the viewer, it would be distancing. So he slowly builds up to it, starting with Obiwan just talking about it, then doing small tricks (â€œThese arenâ€™t the droids youâ€™re looking forâ€¦â€), and then gradually ramping up this reality until we are able to buy the implausibility that Luke Skywalker could â€œuse the forceâ€ to destroy a huge space station.</p>

<p>Here are two more homework assignments: study Kubrickâ€™s â€œThe Shiningâ€ and Bergmanâ€™s â€œFanny and Alexanderâ€ (the directorâ€™s cut if you can get it). Whether youâ€™re fans of those films or not doesnâ€™t matter. The point is, they are relatively realistic, and yet they carefully sprinkle in fantasy elements until the viewer is in a state where heâ€™ll accept almost anything.</p>

<p>[Minor spoilers follow:]</p>

<p>Kubrick begins with by setting a mood: nothing supernatural, but extremely ominous photography and music. He then evokes the idea of ghosts (â€œMy wife is a ghost story and horror film addictâ€) and, about ten minutes into the film, shows a minor incident of ESP. That allows him to go about 20 minutes with no magic. He has laid down a careful nest for magical eggs to hatch later. Watch the movie and pay careful attention to how he prepares us for each new magical element. (E.g. â€œRoom 237â€ gets mentionedâ€”and then forgottenâ€”long before we see inside it. â€œYouâ€™ve always been the caretakerâ€ comes way before the final shot of the filmâ€¦)</p>

<p>Bergman begins his film with an extremely minor piece of magic and even suggests it might be a dream. (Iâ€™m talking about the moving statue.) He then gradually amps up these â€œvisions,â€ each time making them a tiny bit more remarkable and less easy to explain-away as a dream or hallucination. Each one prepares you for the next, bigger one, but he leaves space between them, sometimes half-an-hour or more. So you donâ€™t feel manipulated. The previous haunting is just somewhere in your brain, doing its work.</p>

<p>I urge you do what you can to quit thinking of realistic world-building as a burden. Itâ€™s not. Itâ€™s the challenge and fun of writing fantasy fictionâ€”really of writing all fiction. Think of yourself as a stage magician and give yourself the goal of making your audience believe in magic. (Imagine a magician saying, â€œMy trick is really good. Why do I have to make it believable?â€) Use hints, indirection, telling sensual detail, or whatever you need to get the job done. Because itâ€™s the main point. Itâ€™s not just a boring task you have to do.</p>

